Hello Team;

Where can I find Steve's samples he did for NDC Minnesota 2018?

Thanks!

I want to subscribe to window.resize event. In C# `Js` library project I have this class:
```C#
namespace Js
{
    public static class Browser
    {
        static int counter;
        public static void OnWindowResize()
        {
            Console.WriteLine(++counter);
        }
    }
}
```
In `index.html` file I have added this below `<script type="blazor-boot"></script>`
```JS
<script>
        (function () {
            let onResizeMethod;
            function onResize(event) {
                const assemblyName = 'Js';
                const namespace = 'Js';
                const typeName = 'Browser';
                const methodName = 'OnWindowResize';

                if (onResizeMethod === undefined) {
                    onResizeMethod = Blazor.platform.findMethod(
                        assemblyName,
                        namespace,
                        typeName,
                        methodName
                    );
                }
                if (onResizeMethod !== undefined) {
                    Blazor.platform.callMethod(onResizeMethod, null, []);
                }
            }
            window.addEventListener("resize", onResize);
        })();
</script>
```
***Disclaimer:*** This is the most advanced JavaScript code I have written in my life :smile: and 90% was copied from https://learn-blazor.com/architecture/interop/#calling-a-c-net-method-from-javascript. Maybe there is a simpler solution.

~~It works, but I'm not sure if this is a good general solution to the problem.~~ And the problem is that I want to call potentially slow `Blazor.platform.findMethod` only once and store the result in some variable. My first attempt was to call `Blazor.platform.findMethod` in `load` event handler, but it is to early - Blazor is not initialized yet. ~~The above code works because when the first resize event is generated Blazor is already initialized.~~ To solve the problem elegantly we need something like `blazorInitialized` event. Is it available?

***Update:*** The above code works only if I have the application loaded and then press F5 to refresh the page. It does not work if I open the fresh instance of the browser and then try to load the application for the first time. I get this in console:
```
MonoPlatform.ts:134
Uncaught TypeError: assembly_load is not a function
    at findAssembly (MonoPlatform.ts:134)
    at findType (MonoPlatform.ts:147)
    at Object.findMethod (MonoPlatform.ts:160)
    at onResize ((index):40)
```
***Update 2:*** I have just learned that after page refresh `onResizeMethod` variable preserves its value. My current version of JavaScript code is presented below. I still don't like it.
```JS
<script>
        (function () {
            // initialize to be sure that we call Blazor.platform.findMethod after page refresh
            let onResizeMethod = undefined;
            const assemblyName = 'Js';
            const namespace = 'Js';
            const typeName = 'Browser';
            const methodName = 'OnWindowResize';

            function onResize(event) {
                if (onResizeMethod === undefined) {
                    try {
                        onResizeMethod = Blazor.platform.findMethod(
                            assemblyName,
                            namespace,
                            typeName,
                            methodName
                        );
                    } catch (e) {
                        // catch known exception and ignore, rethrow otherwise
                        if (e.name !== 'TypeError' || e.message !== 'assembly_load is not a function')
                            throw(e);
                    }
                }
                if (onResizeMethod !== undefined) {
                    Blazor.platform.callMethod(onResizeMethod, null, []);
                }
            }
            window.addEventListener('resize', onResize);
        })();
    </script>
```

Hi, I have an existing dll that contains a class whose functions do WebRequest.Create(string url), and WebClient.Encoding. I created an instance of the class with Blazor and it locks up, and doesnt even return the normal styling or default side panel. Any help would be appreciated. The dll contains a private class whose code im not comfortable sharing all of. here is the main functions im using tho.
```C#
        public static T Deserialization<T>(string input) {
            using (var web = new WebClient()) {
                web.Encoding = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8;
                var jsonString = CallServer(input);
                return JsonConvert.DeserializeObject<T>(jsonString);
            }
        }
```
and
````C#
  private static string CallServer(in string apicall) {
            var request = WebRequest.Create($"{BaseURL}/{apicall}"); // Makes the Request to the server
            var response = request.GetResponse(); // Gets the server's response
            var stream = response.GetResponseStream();
            var reader = new StreamReader(stream);
            var responseFromServer = reader.ReadToEnd();
            reader.Close();
            response.Close();

            return responseFromServer;
        }
```

Let's say you keep certain state of the application in AppState (e.g. IsRightMenuOpen , UserLoggedIn,..) But what I would like to see if it's possible to set the content of a component based on a parameter in the AppState. So in the MainContent there is a button that triggers the RightMenu to open and set it's Content (a BlazorComponent)

```
AppState.cs
    public class AppState : IAppState
    {
        public bool IsRightMenuOpen { get; set; }
        public BlazorComponent ContentOfTheRightMenu{ get; set; }
    }
```
```
MainContent.cshtml
@inject IAppState appState
<div>
    <button onclick="@ToggleRightMenu"> Open Right Menu With Content</button>
</div>

@functions{
    void ToggleRightMenu()
    {
        appState.RightContent = //MyComponentName <= How can we instantiate this?
        appState.ToggleRightMenu();
    }
}
```

RightMenu.cshtml
```
@inject IAppState appState
<div>
@appState.ContentOfTheRightMenu
</div>
```

Where I fail to succeed seems to be the following line:
`        appState.RightContent = MyComponentName
`
How can we instantiate a component like this?

An alternative would be to create an enum of each components you want to render and create a switch statement in the RightMenu.cshtml but I doubt that this is the way it should work. Please note that this issue is not about tracking changes or triggering a StateHasChanged on the right component, it's simply setting the component to make it possible to render later.
